  "prompt": "What will happen when Canada allows for perscription heroin in 2017?",
  "response": "In 2017, Canada did not fully legalize prescription heroin, but rather expanded access to medical heroin (diacetylmorphine) for a specific group of people. This was part of a harm reduction strategy for individuals with severe opioid use disorder who have not responded to other treatments.\n\nThe program, known as the Safer Supply or Pharmaceutical Alternative to street drugs, allows certain patients with chronic opioid addiction to receive medical-grade heroin under strict medical supervision. The goals were to:\n\n1. Reduce overdose risks\n2. Decrease transmission of infectious diseases\n3. Lower criminal activity associated with drug procurement\n4. Provide a safer alternative to street drugs\n\nPatients must meet specific criteria and be monitored closely by healthcare professionals. This approach is part of Canada's broader strategy to address the opioid crisis and provide compassionate, evidence-based treatment for people struggling with severe addiction.\n\nThis program was not a blanket legalization of heroin, but a controlled medical intervention for a specific high-risk population.",
